  "text": "Our goal is to develop and standardize spermatogonial cell cryopreservation protocols by testing and modifying previous testicular cryopreservation methods [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . We chose the Indo-Pacific marine Starry goby, Asterropteryx semipunctata Rüppell 1830 (Fig. 1) , as a model. This relatively small, common species attains a maximum adult size of less than 50 mm standard length. Asterropteryx semipunctata belongs to one of the largest families of bony fishes, the Gobiidae, which comprises an overwhelming abundance and biomass of the fish communities in estuaries, mangroves, and coral reef habitats 26 . Small cryptic reef fishes such as gobiids are ecologically important as they use various trophic pathways, particularly detritivory 27 . Moreover, it is estimated that fishes smaller than 50 mm SL, which includes the majority of reef-dwelling gobies, contribute over 25% of the total energy flow in coral reef communities 26 . Successful cryopreservation of the spermatogonial testicular cells of this model fish species will establish a method that may be extended to other fishes and vertebrates.",
